# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1891-cleveland-spiders-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1891-cleveland-spiders-season/1887-cleveland-blues-season] The **1887 Cleveland Blues** baseball team finished with a 39–92 record, last in the American Association during their debut season.
[src:1891-cleveland-spiders-season/1887-cleveland-blues-season] Organized by streetcar tycoon Frank Robison, the team played its home games at National League Park.
[src:1891-cleveland-spiders-season/1888-cleveland-blues-season] The **1888 Cleveland Blues** baseball team finished with a 50–82 record, sixth place in the American Association.
[src:1891-cleveland-spiders-season/1889-cleveland-spiders-season] Before the 1889 season, the Cleveland Blues switched from the American Association to the National League.
[src:1891-cleveland-spiders-season/1889-cleveland-spiders-season] They also earned a new nickname, the **Cleveland Spiders**, because so many of their players were very thin.
[src:1891-cleveland-spiders-season/1889-cleveland-spiders-season] They finished their first season in the National League with a 61–72 record, good enough for sixth place.
[src:1891-cleveland-spiders-season/1890-cleveland-spiders-season] The **1890 Cleveland Spiders** finished with a 44–88 record and a seventh-place finish in the National League.
[src:1891-cleveland-spiders-season/1890-cleveland-spiders-season] The team played six straight home games in Indianapolis, Indiana at Indianapolis Park between July 28 and August 2 against the Brooklyn Bridegrooms and New York Giants.
[src:1891-cleveland-spiders-season/1890-cleveland-spiders-season] It was a former Sunday-games ballpark of the Indianapolis Hoosiers who had folded at the end of the previous season.
[src:1891-cleveland-spiders-season/1891-baltimore-orioles-season] In their last season in the American Association, the **1891 Baltimore Orioles** finished in fourth place (third among teams that played a full schedule) with a record of 71–64.
[src:1891-cleveland-spiders-season/1891-baltimore-orioles-season] After the season, the AA folded, and the Orioles joined the National League.
[src:1891-cleveland-spiders-season/1891-boston-beaneaters-season] The **1891 Boston Beaneaters season** was the 21st season of the franchise.
[src:1891-cleveland-spiders-season/1891-boston-beaneaters-season] The team finished first in the National League with an 87–51–2 (.630) record.
[src:1891-cleveland-spiders-season/1891-boston-beaneaters-season] After trailing the Chicago Colts by seven games in early September, the Beaneaters won 25 of their last 29 games to finish first in the league, 3.5 games ahead of the Colts.
[src:1891-cleveland-spiders-season/1891-boston-reds-season] The **1891 Boston Reds** baseball team finished the season with a 93–42 record and won the American Association championship in their first season in the new league after the demise of the Players' League.
[src:1891-cleveland-spiders-season/1891-boston-reds-season] Thus they became only the second team (after the 1889–1890 Brooklyn Bridegrooms) to win championships in two different leagues in successive seasons, as well as the only team to win the pennant every single season of its existence.
[src:1891-cleveland-spiders-season/1891-boston-reds-season] After the season, the AA also disbanded, and the Reds team folded with the league.
[src:1891-cleveland-spiders-season/1891-cleveland-spiders-season] The **1891 Cleveland Spiders season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1891-cleveland-spiders-season/1891-cleveland-spiders-season] They finished with a 65–74 record and a fifth-place finish in the National League.
[src:1891-cleveland-spiders-season/1891-cleveland-spiders-season] The Spiders moved to a new ballpark in 1891.
[src:1891-cleveland-spiders-season/1891-cleveland-spiders-season] League Park was financed by Spiders owner Frank Robison, and it would be the team's home for the remainder of their existence.
[src:1891-cleveland-spiders-season/1891-cleveland-spiders-season] It would also be home to the Cleveland Indians.
[src:1891-cleveland-spiders-season/1891-cleveland-spiders-season] Patsy Tebeau, the team's starting third baseman, was named manager midway through the season.
[src:1891-cleveland-spiders-season/1891-cleveland-spiders-season] He remained the Spiders manager until his contract was reassigned to the St.
